//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: Secret
//
// KNOWN BUG — this file currently COMPILES AND RUNS, printing `99`. It is deliberately
// left out of `expected-pass.txt`: unlisted-and-failing is the harness's way of
// recording a bug that is not fixed yet, and this file flips green when it is.
//
// A record's nominal identity is its BARE NAME. `typecheck/env.rs::record_body` ends
//
//     let n = self.solver.t.name(&r.name);
//     self.solver.t.nominal(n, args, fields)
//
// and `r.name` is the written identifier with no module path attached — the `Newtype`
// arm of `instantiate` does the same with `decl.name()`. So the nominal identity of a
// record is a projection that drops the declaring module, and two modules that both
// declare `record Secret { code: i64 }` do not merely LOOK alike to the checker: they
// are the SAME TYPE. Not a tag collision downstream, a type-identity collision at the
// source.
//
// That defeats `opaque`. `opaque` is what lets a module hold an invariant its callers
// cannot break — `std::fs` depends on it, where a `File` is a cleanup guard in a field
// and a reachable guard is the same as no guard. Anyone can forge one by declaring a
// same-named, same-shaped record in their own module and handing it over. No `any`, no
// cast, no `is`: the call below type-checks directly.
//
// The same collapse is visible one layer down, where it is a memory-safety shape rather
// than an encapsulation one:
//
//     let fake: any = forge::fake(99);
//     io::println("#{fake is vault::Secret}");   // true
//     let forged = fake as vault::Secret;        // and `as` trusts `is`
//
// because `ctype.rs::tag_name_inner` spells a nominal record `{name}[{fields}]` from
// that same unqualified name.
//
// This is the same class as the closure tag next door (see
// `erased_closure_is_checks_its_signature.neon`): a lossy projection used as an
// identity. It is not fixed here because the fix is not local. The nominal name is read
// back out by `dispatch::nominal_head` and matched against `ir/lower.rs::ast_head`,
// which is `path.last()` of the *written* path — so qualifying the declaration without
// also resolving every written path to its declaring module would break protocol
// dispatch across the whole stdlib. `ordered.rs` additionally matches these names
// against string literals like `"List"`. Qualifying is the right fix; it is a
// multi-site change, and asserting the property here without making it true is exactly
// the failure mode this audit exists to stop.

use std::io;

internal mod vault {
    opaque record Secret { code: i64 }
    fn seal(n: i64) -> Secret { Secret { code: n } }
    fn reveal(s: Secret) -> i64 { s.code }
}

internal mod forge {
    record Secret { code: i64 }
    fn fake(n: i64) -> Secret { Secret { code: n } }
}

fn main() {
    // Should be rejected: a `forge::Secret` is not a `vault::Secret`. Today it prints 99.
    io::println("#{vault::reveal(forge::fake(99))}");
}
